Exercise 4.2.3 - Bivariate Scatterplots

W. Mangrobang

August 27, 2018

Issue Age vs Duration, heat by Attained Age

This is a bit of a trivial example.

We already know via the data dictionary that: attage = issage + duration - 1

Can we confirm that visually?

# load data
data.mortality <- read.csv("/Users/Werlindo/Dropbox/PACP/data/soa_mortality_data.csv")

# load lib(s)
library(ggplot2)

# scatterplot
pid <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(x = issage, y = duration, 
    color = attage)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)
pid

# Save a png
ggsave("ex4_2_3_plot1.png")

Note how uniform the color gradient is moving up and to the right? This seems to confirm the linear relationship between attage and issage.

Exposure Face by Issue Age

pie <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(x = issage, y = log(exposure_face), 
    color = prodcat)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)
pie

This confirms basic intuition:
* Exposure amounts are larger at older ages.
* Whole life policies tend to be issued for younger ages, vs. term, UL. Makes sense as term/UL give more flexibility, something that would likely be a requirement for older people.
